{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"24cf56e2-5f65-4578-bc53-b7d818ff5e7d","content":"With Microsoft.Testing.Platform the switches change names and move after `--` (since the .NET 8 SDK still routes through VSTest by default):\n\n```bash\ndotnet test -- \\\n  --filter \"Category=Integration\" \\\n  --report-trx \\\n  --coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura \\\n  --crashdump \\\n  --hangdump --hangdump-timeout 5m\n```\n\n**Required NuGet packages** in the test project:\n\n| Old feature | New package |\n|---|---|\n| `--logger trx` | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` |\n| `--collect \"Code Coverage\"` | `Microsoft.CodeCoverage.MSBuild` |\n| `--blame-crash` | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CrashDump` |\n| `--blame-hang` | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.HangDump` |\n\nAlso ensure the test `.csproj` has:\n\n```xml\n<EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>   <!-- or equivalent for xUnit/NUnit -->\n<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n<TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>\n```\n\nThe last property enables `dotnet test` to forward args to the new platform on .NET 8. (In .NET 9+ SDK this is automatic.)","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"571086b5-3a19-47b4-a99e-db6600e84969","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating a `dotnet test` command from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MSTest runner) on .NET 8. This is a knowledge question about .NET testing tooling, not a codebase task.\n\nLet me provide the equivalent command for Microsoft.Testing.Platform.\n\nKey differences:\n- `--filter` → `--filter`  (same)\n- `--logger trx` → `--report-trx` \n- `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\"` → `--coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura`\n- `--blame-crash` → `--crashdump`\n\n\n- `--blame-hang` → `--hangdump`\n- `--blame-hang-timeout 5m` → `--hangdump-timeout 5m`\n\nWith Microsoft.Testing.Platform, you can run the test executable directly or use `dotnet test` if the project opts in via `<UseTestingPlatform>true</UseTestingPlatform>`. Starting with .NET 9 SDK, `dotnet test` has native support for Microsoft.Testing.Platform, though for earlier versions you'd pass arguments through with `--`.\n\nOn .NET 8, the test project becomes an executable that you can run directly or via `dotnet run`, and `dotnet test` still works if you configure `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>` and `<TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>`. The command syntax remains consistent—filters and loggers work the same way through the `--` prefix.\n\nBuilding the example command...","outputTokens":1134},"id":"5c91a8e7-9e45-44c5-98cd-93a9241741d7","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:45:12.559Z","parentId":"2bdbe49f-e2d5-41df-9e65-e227963fd507"}
